         <abstract>
            <p>The 67-story, 240-meter BD Bacatá skyscraper in Bogotá architecturally topped out in September 2015, and is on track to become the city’s tallest building. Most remarkable, however, is the way it was financed – BD Bacatá is the world’s first “crowdfunded” skyscraper. Through an Internet platform called Prodigy Network, more than 3,500 Colombian individual investors hold shares in the project, and some have already seen returns of more than 40%. The founder of Prodigy Network, Colombian native Rodrigo Niño, spoke to CTBUH Journal Editor Daniel Safarik about the inspiration and future plans for the New York-based real-estate crowdfunding platform.</p>
